{"/service/ndnp/nmu/batch_nmu_graywolf_ver02/data/sn86063823/0029602580A/1908043001/0416.xml":{"full_text":"We\nAre\nelling Clark's 0\nBEST SIX CORD THREAD\nSpool\nCotton\nAT\n2:\n235\ni S i\nSCHOOL NOTES.\nThe record of last month, the\neighth, showed a steady improvement\nin all lines of school work over that\nof the month before. In fact, there\nhas been a gradual improvement in\nthe work during each month of the\nBchool session. As a whole the month\nly examination testa were very satis\nfactory, for the past month.\nThere were enrolled in all the\nechools during the past month 801\npupils, an increase of about 80 pupils\nover that of 'the same month last\near. This is a splendid growth, when\nwe consider the failure of the fruit\ncrop last year, and the effects of the\nrecent financial panic.\nWith the present flattering crop\nprospects and a large number of con\ntemplated public improvements in\nview for the year, we expect a very\nlarge increase in our school enroll-\nment the coming year.\nThe average per centage of days\nattendance, belonging to each pupil\nwas 93 per cent, an increase of about\n6 per cent over that of the same\nmonth last year. Quite a number of\npupils, too, were taken out of school\ntemporarily on account of the scarlet\nfever scare.\nMrs. R. W. Smith and Mrs. Herbert\nFitzgerald, entertained the graduating\nclass of the grammar school in a de-1\nlightful manner at the home of the\nformer on North Kentucky avenue,\nlast Saturday afternoon. The house\nwas handsomely decorated in green\nand \"white Swastikas, the emblem and\ncolors of the class, the invitations be\ning written in the same manner. Miss\nClark was in charge of amusements,\nhaving arranged a number of progres\nsive games which all enjoyed very\nmuch. Russell Kardwick won the\nprize, which was a Sterling silver\nscarf pin, carrying out the good luck\nA r: \"-J--\nIt v\n\nv rv y; s i I ik 1\nThere isn't a woman\nalive who doesn't like to\nbe comfortable, and but\na few less, who do not\nwant a little spare tinle\nfor themselves with the\nopportunity to wear the\ndainty waists gowns\nof summer.\nThe comfort and the\ntime and the gowns are\npossible for the woman\nwho cooks with gas.\nThere is no heat in\nher kitchen, no dust, no\ndirt, no waiting. She can be through with her work\nbefore the coal-burning woman has begun hers.\nAll of these truths are points in the comfort of\nyour wife. Why not see that she enjoys them? She\nwill bless you for it, and best of all, the Saving in\nUsing Gas Will Pay for it.\nLet her \"Cook with Gas\" and \"Use Crystal Ice\"\nyou'll be surprised how well she stands the summer\nTHE WOMAN WHO COOKS WITH GAS\nftaell\nas Go\nPhone 187 1 Office Salesroom, Guallieur block\nP, S. See About Connections Now\nis\n1\"\n$17.00 to $45.00\nidea. Bettie Fitzgerald gave a piano\nsolo which was much enjoyed. Mary\nCooper and Frieda Smith entertained\nthe gathering with recitations. Delic\nious refreshments were served, Ma\nria Dunn presiding at the punch\nbowl. Bach one present was. given a\nsouvenir picture, of the class. All\nvoted that -they had enjoyed one of\nthe most delightful occasions of their\nlives.\nOn the 19th of this month the alum\nni met at the Central building and\nformed an Alumni Association. Miss\nAlda Smith was elected president;\nArthur Stephens, vice president, and\nMiss Cobean secretary. Committees\nwere appointed to arrange for an alum\nni reception on May 18.\nThe two literary societies will rea\nder a joint program at the Central\nbuilding at 4:30 Friday afternoon.\nAn interesting program has been ar\nranged. This will be the last program\nof the session. The public is cordial\nly invited to attend.\nThe following is an outline program\nfor Commencement week:\nCommencement sermon Sunday\nnight, May 10th.\nCol. Baker's Declamatory Medal\nContest, Monday night. May 11.\nSenior. Class Play, Wednesday night\nMay 13.\nGrammar School Graduating Exer\ncises Thursday night. May 14.\nHigh School Graduating Exercises,\nFriday night, May 15.\nAlumni Reception Monday night,\nMay 18. We hope to give the press\nthe programs, in full next week.\nThe Superintendent has been very\nbusy the past ten days preparing ex\namination questions for the final ex\naminations of the grades. These ex\naminations .will begin the last of next\nweek and will continue until the close\nof school. The outcome of these ex\nam mations with the daily recitation\nwork, will determine the promotions\ninto the next higher grades at the\nclose of school.\no\nRecord Want Ads. Get Results.\nHUNT HJME CO.\nCome to us when you are in trouble with your\npump or wind mill. \"You never miss the water till\nthe well goes dry.\" is a true saying but next to it\nis to have a broken pipe, pump or wind mill.\nWe can help you out promptly and in such\nmanner as to make life pleasant for you again.\nWe also have a nice line of water coolers.\nCall on us.\na\nIndcpenden\nt\nIktare\nC\nGupy\nTamed a Wild Hog.\nCarlsbad, N. M., 'April 29. R. W.\nTansil; Jr., of Chicago, who was writ\nten up several days ago as a wild\nanimal tamer, having tamed a wild\nhog which he roped in the sandhills,\nhas developed his talent somewhat.\nThe wild hog was seen following him\nlike a dog on the streets of Carlsbad\nyesterday. The hog did not pay any\nattention to anyone except Tansil.\nEvery dog in town that scented the\nhog was interested, but kept at a safe\ndistance when the hog exhibited his\ndispleasure by raising his bristles.\nThe dogs satisfied themselves by\nbarking, but not even a bulldog could\nbe scared up with courage or fool\nhardiness to tackle the ho?.\nIt was a novel sight even for old\ntimers who had always regarded the\nwild hog as untamable and dangerous\nR. T. McC.\nPhone R. B. Jones for livery rigs.\n31-3mos.\n1 v. I\n4\nWhat we can save you on a buggy or any other vehicle will go a long\nway toward getting a new set of harness. Come in and get our figures,\nprices speak louder than promise. If we cannot please 